03863nam a22005535i 9780520391444DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203914447 a10.1525/97805203914442doi  a(DE-B1597)653731  a(OCoLC)1390561957  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN1993.5.L3bN38 2023 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43098/09045223/eng/202307121 aNavitski, Rielle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTransatlantic Cinephilia :bFilm Culture between Latin America and France, 1945–1965 /cRielle Navitski. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCinema Cultures in Contact ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Cineclub Movement in Latin America: Transatlantic Cooperation, Local Frictions -- t2. Toward a Global Film Preservation Practice? FIAF and the Emergence of Latin American Archives -- t3. Brokering Art Cinema Latin America and the Festival Circuit -- t4. Film Pedagogy between Latin America and France Training Professionals, Fostering Film Culture -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the two decades after World War II, a vibrant cultural infrastructure of cineclubs, archives, festivals, and film schools took shape in Latin America through the labor of film enthusiasts who often worked in concert with French and France-based organizations. In promoting the emerging concept and practice of art cinema, these film-related institutions advanced geopolitical and class interests simultaneously in a polarized Cold War climate. Seeking to sharpen viewers' critical faculties as a safeguard against ideological extremes, institutions of film culture lent prestige to Latin America's growing middle classes and capitalized on official and unofficial efforts to boost the circulation of French cinema, enhancing the nation's soft power in the wake of military defeat and occupation. As the first book-length, transnational analysis of postwar Latin American film culture, Transatlantic Cinephilia deepens our understanding of how institutional networks have nurtured alternative and nontheatrical cinemas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszLatin Americay20th century. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszLatin Americay20th century. 0aMotion pictureszFrancexInfluence. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520391444?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520391444423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520391444/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles